A STRAWWEIGHT division rivalry will be renewed on a grudge rematch at Emperors Palace in Kempton Park, east of Joburg, on 3 March.

 
  World Boxing Council (WBC) international champion Deejay “The Real Deal” Kriel will defend his hard-earned crown against Xolisa “Gusheshe” Magusha.
 
Kriel and Magusha will clash on the undercard of International Boxing Organisation (IBO) cruiserweight championship between defending champion Kevin “Two Guns” Lerena and Argentinean Dmytro Kucher.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The two top SA mini-flyweight pugilists step on each other’s toes for the second time. On their first meeting, the pair fought an exciting eight-rounder contest, during which Kriel dispatched a points victory against his archival in April.This contest promises to be an exhilarating affair, if the trash talk between the two is anything to go by.Magusha, a South African mini-flyweight champion who has embarked on a new journey to dethrone the WBC international title holder, threw the first verbal jab.The fighter from Queenstown, in the Eastern Cape, said he was coming with everything he had to wrestle the Gauteng-based champ off his crown.
 “I’m coming to get him with everything I have,” said Magusha. 
“In our previous encounter I gave the fight to him with the small mistakes I made. I was aiming for a knockout and it never cameand I was not myself I can’t say what was it. This time around I have corrected those mistakes,” said Magusha.The 27-year-old fighter said his confidence was sky-high as he would be fighting as a national champion.“Winning is a morale boost, because I’m coming to this fight highly motivated. This time I’m also a champion. There’ll be no rest for him inside the ring,” said the Eastern Cape southpaw.Kriel remained optimistic, saying come fight night he’ll defend his crown.“I’m confident that I’ll successfully defend my title. I can’t predict anything, but I’m sure about a victory, even Magusha knows it.“I guess this time I’ll do better. I always step in the ring to win,” said Kriel.The 22-year-old WBC international champion from Boksburg, Ekurhuleni, registered a unanimous points victory against Philipino Dexter Alimento to claim the belt.